  "observation": "Brainstorm triggered by plateau. 4 proposals generated.",
  "suggestion": "The plateau reflects convergence within a static utility landscape. The organisms have found a local maximum in the 3-part fitness function given fixed rules. Breaking through requires either: (1) a new constraint system (metabolism) that prevents joint optimization of all objectives, (2) a dynamic/interaction-dependent fitness function that has no fixed optimum, or (3) heterogeneous selection pressures that reward divergence rather than convergence. The meta-pattern: plateaus in evolutionary systems indicate the search space is too simple relative to the problem; increase problem complexity, not just population size.; [hard] Introduce Metabolic Energy System: Organisms have explicit energy stores (ATP-like). Cell operations, movement, and beauty displays have energy costs. Organisms must harvest energy from the environment or consume other organisms. Energy becomes the constraint that forces strategic trade-offs between growth, beauty display, and survival. — Current fitness likely being optimized within a single optimization basin. Metabolism introduces competing resource allocation problems—you cannot maximize all fitness components simultaneously anymore. Organisms must make strategic choices (e.g., 'invest in beauty now or save energy for reproduction?'). This expands the strategy space exponentially and breaks local convergence. The plateau exists because the 3-part fitness function is being jointly optimized; metabolic constraints create a much larger Pareto frontier.; [medium] Temporal & Interaction-Based Beauty Scoring: Replace static morphological beauty with dynamic beauty that emerges from time-varying behaviors and organism-organism interactions. Example: synchronized movement with neighbors, rhythmic growth pulses, coordinated color changes. Beauty only scores when patterns are temporally consistent. — Plateau suggests organisms found a static morphological 'sweet spot.' By making beauty time-dependent and interaction-dependent, you eliminate the static optima. Organisms cannot simply grow a pretty shape and stop—they must continuously perform beauty behaviors, and beauty emerges from interaction networks. This creates a moving target that forces ongoing evolutionary search.; [medium] Introduce Ecological Niche Differentiation: Partition the world into distinct environmental zones (e.g., high-light, low-light, nutrient-rich, nutrient-poor regions) with different selection pressures and resource availability. Reward specialization—a specialist in one zone outcompetes generalists, but is unfit elsewhere. Force organisms to either specialize or migrate. — Uniform environment drove convergence to a single global optimum. Multiple niches with conflicting selection pressures prevent convergence and create arms races (specialists evolve → generalists adapt → specialists counter-adapt). Speciation and diversification become fitness-positive. Population maintains multiple local optima instead of collapsing to one.",
